Vector Space Models

  • Vector Space Models (VSM): Represent documents/words as a vector in a vector space: Vectors that are closer together in space are semantically similar and vectors that are far apart are semantically distant. (Turney & Pantel, 2010)

  • Idea very much pre-CSS

  • Stems from information retrieval (Salton, 1971)

  • We start with: documents as vectors

Documents as Vectors

Basic idea (& some notation ð¤)

  • Let \(w\) be a word

  • Let \(D = (w_1, w_2, w_3, â¦, w_N)\) be a document consisting of sequences of words. For example, \(D_1\): âI like fruit like apple and kiwiâ.

  • Let \(V\) be the vocabulary, with size \(|V|\) = \(N\) (number of unique words)

Documents as Vectors

  • Idea ð¡: We can represent each document \(D\) via a frequency vector including all its words:

  • Take example sentence \(D_1\): âI like fruit like apple and kiwiâ

  • \(D_1\) = (I, like, fruit, like, apple, and, kiwi)

  • \(V\) = (I, like, fruit, apple, and, kiwi), \(|V|\) = 6

Documents as Vectors

  • Idea ð¡: We can represent each document \(D\) via a frequency vector described by its words which is located in an \(N\)-dimensional space:

  • Take example sentence \(D_1\): âI like fruit like apple and kiwiâ

  • Document represented as seven vectors \(D_1 = (w_1, w_2, w_3, â¦, w_7)\), one for each \(w_i\), of length \(|V|\) = \(N\) = 6 (our dimensions) including only 0/1 (one-hot-encoding):

\[V_{D_1} = \sum_{i=1}^{7} V_{wi} =\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0\\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1\\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ 1\\ 1\end{pmatrix}\]

Documents as Vectors

  • Idea ð¡: We can represent each document \(D\) via a frequency vector described by its words which is located in an \(N\)-dimensional space:

  • Take example sentence \(D_1\): âI like fruit like apple and kiwiâ

  • Document represented as seven vectors \(D_1 = (w_1, w_2, w_3, â¦, w_7)\), one for each \(w_i\), of length \(|V|\) = \(N\) = 6 (our dimensions) including only 0/1 (one-hot-encoding):

  • Document then represend via a single word-frequency vector [1, 2, 1, 1, 1, 1]

Documents as Vectors

  • Using the vector representation, we can now represent the sentence âI like fruit like apple and kiwiâ in a \(N\)-dimensional vector space.

  • To create a 2-dimensional vector space, we only consider words âkiwiâ as the \(x\)-axis and and âlikeâ as the \(y\)-axis:

Documents as Vectors

  • Now, we letâs add two other sentences to see how they compare: âI like kiwi, only kiwiâ (Sentence 2) and âI only like vegetables, especially potatoâ (Sentence 3).

Documents as Vectors

  • We can now calculate the distance between these vectors
  • Use distance/similarity metrics (e.g., Euclidean distance, cosine similarity, etc).

Documents as Vectors in R

  • In R, we can compute similarities between word vectors:
    • set-up vectors (e.g., sentence 1 as [1, 2] in 2-dimensional space)
    • compute similarity/distance, e.g.Â using cosine function from lsa
  • However, packages like textreuse make this bit easier (and offer more/better methods)
Code 
library("lsa")
sent_1 <- c(1, 2)
sent_2 <- c(2, 1)
sent_3 <- c(0, 1)
cosine(sent_1, sent_3)
          [,1]
[1,] 0.8944272
Code 
cosine(sent_1, sent_2)
     [,1]
[1,]  0.8

Identifying meaning through semantic spaces (sparse VSM): Overview ð

  • Methods: Documents as sparse vectors (for now) in \(N\)-dimensional space

  • Use for: Text similarity, text-reuse, plagiarism detection, media bias

  • Examplary studies:

    • for measuring media bias: Mozer et al. (2020)

  • Packages:

    • lsa
    • textreuse and related publication (Mullen, 2020)

Word as Vectors

We already know that we can also represent word as vectors!

Remember the one-hot-encoding of the sentence I like fruit like apple and kiwi?

\[V_{D_1} = \sum_{i=1}^{7} V_{wi} =\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0\\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1\\ 0\end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \\ 1 \\ 1\\ 1\end{pmatrix}\]
